in all life, as we know it, there is no stopping-place‚ no pause. From the beginning of the universe until now creation is life, and life is as a river pouring forth and for ever pouring forth. The whole of terrestrial existence is one with universal existence. The whole of terrestrial life, from the first embryo until now, and as long as it may last, is indivisible. And the individual man, person though he be, is indivisible from the stream of life.

Yet to each generation, and to each individual, is given the supreme honour of giving to the race its future environment, choosing within certain limits what that future shall be. If our wills are free, if the animals about us have any power to do or not to do, if God would have freemen and not slaves, if there be any truth in our conclusion that creation is life and life is autono- mous, we may be quite sure that the condition of the world into which any man is born is not entirely according to God's will. Our sense of wrong testifies that life has deviated from God's will more or less.
